10:54.854 --> 11:01.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
knowing that the Taliban doesn't
control urban
terrain, like ISIS does in Iraq,
for example.

11:01.160 --> 11:04.597 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't control Kabul. They
don't control
any major provincial capitals.

11:04.697 --> 11:09.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So these kind of urban attacks
are done more
for psychological operations,
rather than

11:09.168 --> 11:11.037 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
control of territory.

11:11.137 --> 11:13.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, what's the
distinction,
though? You say they don't
control urban areas,

11:13.806 --> 11:18.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but they're able to pull off
something like
this, almost 30 people killed,
hundreds badly

11:18.511 --> 11:20.346 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
hurt.

11:20.446 --> 11:24.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SETH JONES: Yes. What it shows,
they do control
a fair amount of rural terrain.
They also

11:24.617 --> 11:29.722 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have cell structures that
operate in cities.
So while the government controls
most of the

11:29.822 --> 11:35.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
urban terrain in cities like
Kabul, the Taliban
does have an ability to push in
resources

11:35.295 --> 11:37.063 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and conduct attacks.

11:37.163 --> 11:40.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it certainly has an effect
on the population
there, which believes the
government can't

11:40.433 --> 11:42.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
secure it at all times.

11:42.402 --> 11:48.274 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And so that
psychological effect,
why isn't that the same or
almost the same

11:48.374 --> 11:50.143 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
as having actual control?

11:50.243 --> 11:56.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SETH JONES: Well, it's different
because the
Taliban does a lot. It
administers justice

11:56.516 --> 12:00.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in areas that it controls. It
taxes the local
population.

12:00.486 --> 12:06.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It has a political structure,
almost a political
state apparatus, in areas that
it controls.

12:06.292 --> 12:11.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It doesn't have that in cities
like Kabul.
What it has is really a military
and intelligence

12:11.497 --> 12:16.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
infrastructure, but it wants the
political
architecture to go with that. So
this -- it

12:16.903 --> 12:18.905 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is part of a longer-term
campaign.

12:19.005 --> 12:25.612 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What does this
say, Seth Jones,
about the standing of Afghan
security forces,

12:25.712 --> 12:30.049 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which we know the U.S. has been
trying to
build up for years now?

12:30.149 --> 12:35.922 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SETH JONES: Look, there are
plenty of challenges
with the Afghan national
security forces.

12:36.022 --> 12:41.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The higher-end forces that
responded to this
today, the intelligence forces,
the Afghan

12:41.694 --> 12:48.034 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
commandos, the Qataha (ph), some
of the higher-end
army forces, are pretty good.

12:48.134 --> 12:53.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the general state of the
police and a
lot of the army kandaks are of
mixed quality.

12:54.040 --> 12:59.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the problem that we're
seeing is,
they're not very proactive in
pushing out

12:59.278 --> 13:03.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against the Taliban in rural
areas. And so
the fight is now coming to them
in the cities.

13:03.916 --> 13:07.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you assess
what the
U.S. is doing? We know the
president decided

13:08.087 --> 13:14.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to keep American troops in
Afghanistan longer,
but what is the -- what role is
the posture

13:14.394 --> 13:20.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- is U.S. posture playing right
now in this
battle between Afghans -- the
Afghan government

13:20.933 --> 13:22.869 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and the Taliban?

13:22.969 --> 13:25.571 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SETH JONES: Well, first of all,
the U.S. president
has said that the number of
troops, it will

13:25.672 --> 13:31.811 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
continue to come down through
January of 2017.
So now we're roughly 10,000. He
said they're

13:31.911 --> 13:35.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
going to go down to about 10,000
-- about
5,500.

13:35.348 --> 13:41.854 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's also restricted the ability
to conduct
strikes against the Taliban a
few other groups

13:41.954 --> 13:47.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like the Haqqani Network without
-- unless
there's a good example of those
forces conducting

13:48.027 --> 13:52.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
attacks against Americans. So,
there are also
limits on what the U.S. can do
training out

13:52.832 --> 13:54.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in the field.

13:54.667 --> 13:58.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the U.S. has sort of limited
its ability
to impact this, except in
response to these

13:59.005 --> 14:00.239 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
kinds of attacks.

14:00.339 --> 14:03.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we are
continuing to
watch the story.

14:03.476 --> 14:05.044 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Seth Jones, we thank you for
joining us.

14:05.144 --> 14:06.646 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SETH JONES: Thanks, Judy.

14:06.746 --> 14:12.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now: to another
major American
military campaign, against ISIS.

14:12.485 --> 14:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yesterday, Secretary of Defense
Ash Carter
announced that some 217 more
American troops

14:18.157 --> 14:24.363 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
would soon go to Iraq, pushing
the American
strength there to over 4,000.
The U.S. will

14:24.464 --> 14:30.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
also send Apache fast-attack
helicopters,
which will help protect the
Iraqi army as

14:30.303 --> 14:34.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it begins its advance on the
ISIS-held city
of Mosul.

14:34.140 --> 14:40.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. also announced more
than $400 million
in aid to the Kurdish Peshmerga
forces in

14:40.780 --> 14:42.648 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Northern Iraq.

14:42.749 --> 14:46.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on all this and the
wider war against
ISIS, I'm joined by President
Obama's special

14:47.086 --> 14:51.624 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
envoy to the coalition fighting
ISIS, Brett
McGurk.

14:51.724 --> 14:53.559 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome back to the program.

14:53.659 --> 14:53.993 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRETT MCGURK, Special
Presidential Envoy for
the Global Coalition to Counter
ISIL: Thank

14:54.093 --> 14:55.828 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
you, Judy.

14:55.928 --> 14:59.565 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why is -- and why
is the president
sending these additional U.S.
advisers?

14:59.665 --> 15:05.071 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRETT MCGURK: Well, the
president really instructed
our team about four or five
months ago to

15:05.171 --> 15:08.441 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
do all we can to accelerate the
campaign.

15:08.541 --> 15:13.613 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it took a while, Judy, to
get particularly
the Iraqi forces in place to be
able to stand

15:13.713 --> 15:18.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
up, maneuver, conduct offensive
operations.
And we're now seeing some
success. They liberated

15:18.684 --> 15:24.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ramadi just last week. They
liberated a really
critical strategic town called
Al-Hit just

15:24.924 --> 15:27.460 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the west of Ramadi in the
center of the
Euphrates Valley.

15:27.560 --> 15:33.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's been a stronghold of ISIL.
And they liberated
that last week. And what we're
now in position

15:33.199 --> 15:38.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do with the Iraqi security
forces is conduct
pressure against ISIL on
multiple simultaneous

15:38.337 --> 15:42.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fronts. That's the Euphrates
Valley and Anbar
Province, where operations will
continue,

15:42.475 --> 15:44.710 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and now beginning up toward
Mosul.

15:44.811 --> 15:48.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this is really a package
that's been in
development for some time, and
we think it

15:48.881 --> 15:53.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will give the Iraqis some unique
capabilities
as it moves on Mosul. Mosul is a
little different

15:54.053 --> 15:59.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
than Ramadi. Logistically, the
Iraqis have
the travel a little further than
they're usually

15:59.425 --> 16:01.260 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
used to.

16:01.360 --> 16:03.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we will be helping with
logistics, we will
be helping with sustainment.
And, of course,

16:03.663 --> 16:08.134 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
when they come into combat, we
will be ready
to support them with Apache
helicopters and

16:08.234 --> 16:10.002 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
some other enablers.

16:10.102 --> 16:15.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But sending U.S.
forces or
U.S. advisers closer to the
front lines, is

16:15.107 --> 16:19.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this an acknowledgment the Iraqi
military
is really not able to do the job
alone??

16:19.879 --> 16:25.251 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRETT MCGURK: No, it's really --
you have
to look at the topography of the
battlefield.

16:25.351 --> 16:32.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Ramadi, for example, when
Ramadi fell,
the president ordered a
detachment of U.S.

16:32.992 --> 16:37.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
special forces to Taqaddum Air
Base, which
is sandwiched right in between
Ramadi and

16:37.363 --> 16:42.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Fallujah. It's only about 25
kilometers or
so from the front lines.

16:42.368 --> 16:48.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mosul is -- we have to be with
the Iraqis
in their headquarters, and their
headquarters

16:48.140 --> 16:52.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as they move toward Mosul will
change. They
will be kind of mobile. So we
will be with

16:52.545 --> 16:56.682 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Iraqi commanders, advising
and assisting
what they're doing, which is
very similar

16:56.782 --> 16:59.752 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to what we did in Anbar
province.

16:59.852 --> 17:04.190 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in Anbar, where we have two
facilities,
it's a little more stationary.
So, we're on

17:04.290 --> 17:07.760 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
base. We're advising and
assisting. In Mosul,
there will be a lot of -- it
will be a little

17:07.860 --> 17:12.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more dynamic. So, we want to
make sure that
our best advisers are with the
headquarters,

17:12.798 --> 17:16.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with the Iraqi commanders as
they're planning
and conducting their operations.

17:16.335 --> 17:18.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is it fair the
call this mission
creep?

17:18.638 --> 17:23.643 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRETT MCGURK: No, it's the exact
same mission
in Mosul that we have been doing
in Anbar

17:23.743 --> 17:27.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
province. It's just we're moving
into that
phase in Mosul now. It's the
same mission.

17:28.080 --> 17:32.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The only difference is Apache
helicopters.
But we were prepared to use
Apache helicopters.

17:33.019 --> 17:36.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The president authorized it for
Ramadi, but
given the situation, given the
fact that the

17:36.856 --> 17:40.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iraqis were having an awful lot
of success,
and given the urban environment,
we determined

17:40.293 --> 17:42.128 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that it really wasn't needed.

17:42.228 --> 17:46.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, in Mosul, it's a complex
terrain. It's
the citadel of Da'esh. They're
well-defended

17:46.732 --> 17:51.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there. So, we think Apaches can
make a difference.
We discussed this with the Iraqi
government.

17:51.570 --> 17:54.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Everything we do in Iraq is with
the consent
of the Iraqi government. This is
something

17:55.074 --> 17:59.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Prime Minister Abadi wanted. And
we found
a formula that we think will be
effective.

17:59.245 --> 18:02.615 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let me ask
you about
some criticism we're hearing
from the other

18:02.715 --> 18:08.387 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
side. The "NewsHour" spoke today
with retired
Army Colonel Derek Harvey, who,
as you know,

18:08.487 --> 18:11.757 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
advised General David Petraeus
in Iraq for
a number of years.

18:11.857 --> 18:17.029 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He told us he thinks these steps
represent
insufficient resources in the
first place

18:17.129 --> 18:23.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the administration and poor
execution by
the administration working with
the Iraqis.

18:23.402 --> 18:27.873 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRETT MCGURK: Well, I worked in
Iraq with
David Petraeus back in those
days, too, and

18:27.974 --> 18:31.544 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ambassador Crocker. It's a
different time
now. We're not fighting a war.

18:31.644 --> 18:36.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Iraqis are fighting the war.
We're in
the middle of liberating all of
Anbar province.

18:36.582 --> 18:40.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Again, we liberated Ramadi. That
was done
with Iraqis. We're now moving
west up the

18:41.053 --> 18:46.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Euphrates Valley. This is being
done with
Iraqis. The strategic town of
Al-Hit is critical

18:46.392 --> 18:50.730 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because it opens up a free
expressway from
Ramadi to Haditha.

18:50.830 --> 18:55.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a town of Haditha, which
has been
under siege by Da'esh for almost
two years.

18:55.401 --> 18:59.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're now in a position to break
that siege.
So, we're having an awful lot of
success.

18:59.672 --> 19:06.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a different campaign than
it was in 2007-2008.
You know, Americans are not
doing the fighting.

19:06.846 --> 19:13.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
We are advising. We're
assisting. We're providing
devastating air support and
special operations.

19:13.753 --> 19:16.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, there are things we of
course don't
talk about much. We have special
operations

19:16.856 --> 19:21.360 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and special forces in Northern
Iraq. They're
very effective against the
leadership of Da'esh.

19:21.460 --> 19:26.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, you know, they're doing
a great job.
And everything we do, again,
Judy, is with

19:26.232 --> 19:30.870 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the consent of the Iraqi
government. This
is not a situation in which
we're an occupying

19:30.970 --> 19:35.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
force. We're just -- it's a
very, very different,
much more complex, much more
challenging situation

19:35.808 --> 19:37.710 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
than 2007.

19:37.810 --> 19:42.648 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we believe that the most
sustainable way
to do this is to get the Iraqis
fighting,

19:42.748 --> 19:44.550 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to empower locals.

19:44.650 --> 19:46.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you can
understand why
people look at this, and they
see more troops

19:47.019 --> 19:50.556 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
going, they see Apache
helicopters going,
and they want to know what's
going on.

19:50.656 --> 19:54.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But just in the time we have
left, I want
to ask you about Syria, the
fight against

19:54.994 --> 20:01.467 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ISIS there. First of all, do you
see real
evidence that the Russians have
begun to go

20:01.567 --> 20:07.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
after ISIS, rather than going
after the rebels
who are fighting the Assad
regime?

20:08.007 --> 20:11.310 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRETT MCGURK: Well, we have seen
a bit of
a shift.

20:11.410 --> 20:16.148 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And if you look at the
statistics that we
talk about, when Russia came in,
they claimed

20:16.248 --> 20:19.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to be going after ISIL. And that
just simply
wasn't true. About 80 percent of
their strikes

20:19.952 --> 20:23.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
were against opposition, the
moderate opposition
forces.

20:23.522 --> 20:27.426 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Since the cessation of
hostilities came in
place, their airstrikes have
shifted quite

20:27.526 --> 20:33.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a bit. And at one point, it was
about 70 percent
against ISIL. And they helped
the Syrian forces

20:33.699 --> 20:35.501 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
retake Palmyra.

20:35.601 --> 20:40.272 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, look, we have a very long
way to go in
Syria. There is no question.
President Obama

20:40.372 --> 20:45.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
spoke with President Putin
yesterday. We will
be traveling with the president
and secretary

20:45.277 --> 20:50.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tonight to Saudi Arabia to meet
with the GCC
and discuss the situation in
Syria.

20:50.616 --> 20:54.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in the war against ISIL in
Syria, we're
very focused, again, east of the
Euphrates

20:54.920 --> 20:58.991 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
River, on moving down and
constricting Al-Raqqa,
its center of operations. And
that's something

20:59.091 --> 21:02.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we're also looking at
accelerating some
of our efforts there.

21:02.428 --> 21:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we're also working to again
close off
that last about 98-kilometer
strip of border

21:07.166 --> 21:10.936 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that ISIL still controls with
Turkey. And
there's very active fighting
ongoing there

21:11.036 --> 21:16.108 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now, which we're supporting.
It's a very complex,
very dynamic situation. There
are no shortcuts.

